<DOC><DOCNO> AP880526-0064 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-88 0548EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief 730   05-26 0728</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief, 730</SECOND><HEAD>Safety Commission to Ban Most Lawn Darts</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Consumer Product Safety Commission hasvoted to ban most lawn darts, saying the pointed metal toys presenta danger of death or serious injury.   Lawn darts, which have long metal tips, have become popular as ayard game. They are tossed through the air, with the player tryingto sticking the points into the ground in or near a target.   Three children, aged 4, 7 and 13, have been killed in accidentsinvolving the darts in recent years, according to commissionrecords. In addition, an estimated 670 lawn-dart injuries aretreated annually at hospital emergency rooms.   The ban, voted Wednesday, now goes back to the commission staffto develop a formal rulemaking to enforce the ban and to solicitcomment from the public before being returned to the commissionersfor a vote on a final ban, likely in late summer or fall.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Federal Pollution-Fighters Find Bad Air in Their Own Offices</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Many of the nation's pollution-fighters at theheadquarters of the Environmental Protection Agency have beengasping and wheezing from an air pollution problem apparentlycaused by new carpeting.   Sixty-five employees have sought medical attention and sevencan't enter the building at all because of their reactions whenthey do, William Hirzy, president-elect of Local 2050 of theNational Federation of Federal Employees, said Wednesday.   Hirzy said he was ``90 percent certain'' the reactions came fromexposure to phenylcyclohexene, a gas given off by the backing ofnew rugs the agency has been installing in the building used by5,100 employees.   The agency has stopped putting in new carpets, but CharlesGrizzle, assistant administrator for administration, saidphenylcyclohexene had not been fixed definitely as the cause of theproblem and ``I don't see any reason to rip up the carpets until weare sure.''</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>House Votes to Lift Curb on Interstate Ads for Gambling</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A bill approved by the House would would allowadvertising across state lines of gambling activities, such ascasino gambling, church raffles and bingo games.   The House voted Wednesday to remove a federal prohibition oninterstate advertising of gambling.   Under current law, states can advertise state-conductedlotteries only in adjacent states that also have lotteries. Allother advertising of games of chance is prohibited.   The bill, approved by voice vote and sent to the Senate, wouldstill allow individual states to restrict such advertising.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>Virginia Congressmen Join Fight Against Development at Civil WarSite</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   While members of Congress signed on asco-sponsors of a bill to protect the Manassas National Battlefieldin northern Virginia from commercial development, the Virginiadelegation had been quiet.   On Wednesday, Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., changed that byintroducing a bill he says is better than anything else that hasbeen offered in the effort to stop developers from putting ashopping mall next to the park.   Rep. Stan Parris, another northern Virginia congressman,immediately said he would be a co-sponsor.   ``I think everyone should be pleased that a Virginian hasfinally said no to the shopping mall,'' said Rep. Michael Andrews,D-Texas.   Andrews and Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., and 166 co-sponsors havea bill pending that calls for acquisition by the InteriorDepartment of about 600 acres next to the battlefield where theHazel-Peterson Co. wants to build the shopping center, homes andoffices.   Wolf said his bill is better because it calls for ``legislativetaking'' of the land, a faster process than going through theInterior Department.</TEXT><HEAD>___</HEAD><HEAD>U.S. Government Opens Another Front in Oranges Fight</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government is trying on another front toboost sales American oranges and orange juice in Japan.   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter announced Wednesdaythat he has accepted a Florida citrus industry petition for aformal investigation of Japanese restrictions on orange and juiceimports as unfair trade practices.   The restrictions include import quotas and a requirement thatimported juice be blended with home-grown juice.   Yeutter's office already is pursuing the orange dispute at otherlevels. After months of unsuccessful negotiations with the Japanesegovernment, it moved earlier this month to have the Japanese orangeimport quotas _ along with those on beef imports _ declared illegalunder international trading rules by GATT, the General Agreement onTariffs and Trade.</TEXT></DOC>